WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:13.420 --> 00:00:15.996
Probably not a surprise to you,
也许你不会惊讶，

2
00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:18.156
but I don't like to be in a hospital
我不喜欢呆在医院，

3
00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:19.836
or go to a hospital.
或去医院看病。

4
00:00:19.859 --> 00:00:21.636
Do you?
你喜欢吗？

5
00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:24.116
I'm sure many of you feel the same way, right?
我相信你们很多人 有同样的感受，对吗？

6
00:00:24.140 --> 00:00:28.155
But why? Why is it that we hate hospitals so much?
但为什么？为什么我们如此厌恶医院？

7
00:00:28.180 --> 00:00:30.540
Or is it just a fact of life we have to live with?
这不是生活中不可避免的一个事实吗？

8
00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:33.260
Is it the crappy food?
是难吃的病号饭？

9
00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:36.356
Is it the expensive parking?
是昂贵的停车费？

10
00:00:36.380 --> 00:00:38.156
Is it the intense smell?
是强烈的药水气味？

11
00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:40.060
Or is it the fear of the unknown?
或者是对未知的恐惧？

12
00:00:40.860 --> 00:00:43.860
Well, it's all of that, and it's more.
全部都有，而且不止这些。

13
00:00:44.980 --> 00:00:47.476
Patients often have to travel long distances
病人常常需要赶很长一段路

14
00:00:47.500 --> 00:00:49.100
to get to their nearest hospital,
才能到最近的医院，

15
00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:54.076
and access to hospital care is becoming more and more an issue
而且在美国的乡村地区

16
00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:55.756
in rural areas,
要获得医院护理

17
00:00:55.780 --> 00:00:57.076
in the US,
越来越成问题，

18
00:00:57.100 --> 00:00:59.900
but also in sparsely populated countries like Sweden.
在瑞典这样人口稀少的国家也是如此。

19
00:01:01.060 --> 00:01:03.940
And even when hospitals are more abundant,
即便当医院资源更加充裕时，

20
00:01:04.860 --> 00:01:06.876
typically the poor and the elderly
特别是穷人和老人也通常

21
00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:09.956
have trouble getting care because they lack transportation
因为缺乏便利，廉价的交通

22
00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:12.420
that is convenient and affordable to them.
而无法获得医疗服务。

23
00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:18.196
And many people are avoiding hospital care altogether,
许多人甚至完全避开医疗治疗，

24
00:01:18.220 --> 00:01:20.236
and they miss getting proper treatment
为了节省开销而错过了

25
00:01:20.260 --> 00:01:21.460
due to cost.
合适的治疗。

26
00:01:22.540 --> 00:01:26.236
We see that 64 percent of Americans
我们可以看到，有64%的美国人

27
00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:28.820
are avoiding care due to cost.
因为费用问题而避免医疗服务。

28
00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:33.636
And even when you do get treatment,
即便你接受了治疗，

29
00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:35.740
hospitals often make us sicker.
医院也常常会让我们病情加重。

30
00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:41.900
Medical errors are reported to be the third cause of death in the US,
据报道，医疗事故是 美国的第三大致死因素，

31
00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:46.356
just behind cancer and heart disease,
仅次于癌症和心脏疾病，

32
00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:47.860
the third cause of death.
第三大死因。

33
00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:51.596
I'm in health care for over 20 years now,
我从事医疗行业已经20多年了，

34
00:01:51.620 --> 00:01:57.300
and I witness every day how broken and how obsolete our hospital system is.
每天我都见证着我们的医院系统 是如此的破败和落后。

35
00:01:58.260 --> 00:01:59.996
Let me give you two examples.
让我给你们两个例子。

36
00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:03.276
Four in 10 Japanese medical doctors
10个日本医生中有4个，

37
00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:06.116
and five in 10 American medical doctors
10个美国医生中有5个

38
00:02:06.140 --> 00:02:07.340
are burnt out.
已经在超负荷工作了。

39
00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:10.796
In my home country, the Netherlands,
在我的祖国，荷兰，

40
00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:12.996
only 17 million people live there.
只有1700万人口。

41
00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:17.780
We are short 125,000 nurses over the coming years.
在未来几年，我们会缺少12.5万名护士。

42
00:02:19.740 --> 00:02:21.476
But how did we even end up here,
但我们是怎么走到这一步的，

43
00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:24.316
in this idea of placing all kinds of sick people
把所有病人都集中到

44
00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:26.020
together in one big building?
一幢大楼里的？

45
00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:30.220
Well, we have to go back to the Ancient Greeks.
这就要追溯到古希腊时期。

46
00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:34.156
In 400 BC, temples for cure were erected
公元前400年，人们建造了治病的庙宇，

47
00:02:34.180 --> 00:02:36.676
where people could go to get their diagnosis,
病人在那里可以得到诊断，

48
00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:39.156
their treatment and their healing.
治疗和恢复。

49
00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:42.596
And then really for about 2,000 years,
在之后的2000年间，

50
00:02:42.620 --> 00:02:45.116
we've seen religious care centers
我们看到了教会的护理中心，

51
00:02:45.140 --> 00:02:48.716
all the way up to the Industrial Revolution,
直到进入工业革命时期，

52
00:02:48.740 --> 00:02:53.900
where we've seen hospitals being set up as assembly lines
我们看到医院基于工业革命的原则，

53
00:02:55.820 --> 00:02:58.316
based on the principles of the Industrial Revolution,
像流水线那样尽快产出产品，

54
00:02:58.340 --> 00:02:59.796
to produce efficiently
提升了生产效率，

55
00:02:59.820 --> 00:03:02.556
and get the products, the patients in this case,
在医院的案例中，产品变成了病人，

56
00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:04.940
out of the hospital as soon as possible.
以让他们尽快走出医院。

57
00:03:06.340 --> 00:03:10.636
Over the last century, we've seen lots of interesting innovations.
在过去一个世纪中， 我们看到了很多有趣的创新。

58
00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:13.116
We figured out how to make insulin.
我们找到了制造胰岛素的方法。

59
00:03:13.140 --> 00:03:15.916
We invented pacemakers and X-ray,
我们发明了起搏器和X光，

60
00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:20.540
and we even came into this wonderful new era of cell and gene therapies.
我们甚至进入了细胞和 基因治疗的奇妙新时代。

61
00:03:21.620 --> 00:03:26.116
But the biggest change to fix our hospital system altogether
但修复我们医疗系统的最大变革

62
00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:28.156
is still ahead of us.
仍然没有到来。

63
00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:31.036
And I believe it's time now, we have the opportunity,
我相信现在是时候了，我们有机会

64
00:03:31.060 --> 00:03:34.116
to revolutionize the system altogether
去彻底改革整个系统，

65
00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:36.916
and forget about our current hospital system.
完全忘掉我们现有的医院系统。

66
00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:39.156
I believe it's time to create a new system
我相信是时候创造新的，

67
00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:41.740
that revolves around health care at home.
以家庭护理为中心的系统了。

68
00:03:43.660 --> 00:03:46.236
Recent research has shown
最近的研究发现，

69
00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:49.516
that 46 percent of hospital care
46%的医院治疗

70
00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:51.060
can move to the patient's home.
可以转移到患者家中进行。

71
00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:53.996
That's a lot.
这个数量相当庞大。

72
00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:58.356
And that's mainly for those patients who suffer from chronic diseases.
这主要是针对那些患有慢性疾病的病人。

73
00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:01.356
With that, hospitals can and should
对此，医院可以，而且应该

74
00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:05.316
reduce to smaller, agile and mobile care centers
精简到专注于急症治疗的 更加小型，灵活和移动的

75
00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:06.620
focused on acute care.
医疗中心。

76
00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:13.756
So things like neonatology, intensive care, surgery and imaging
比如新生儿，重症监护，手术和成像，

77
00:04:13.780 --> 00:04:15.836
will still remain at the hospitals,
这些可以仍然保留在医院，

78
00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:18.620
at least I believe for the foreseeable future.
至少在可预见的未来是这样。

79
00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:22.396
A few weeks ago, I met a colleague
几周前，我遇到一个同事,

80
00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:25.676
whose mom was diagnosed with incurable cancer,
她妈妈被诊断患了癌症，时日无多。

81
00:04:25.700 --> 00:04:27.516
and she said, "Niels, it's hard.
她说：“尼尔斯，真的很艰难。

82
00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:31.300
It's so hard when we know that she's got only months to live.
当知道她只有几个月生命时， 一切都变得如此艰难。

83
00:04:32.380 --> 00:04:34.436
Instead of playing with the grandchildren,
她无法再和孙子们玩耍了，

84
00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:37.956
she now has to travel three times a week
现在她每周需要外出三次，

85
00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:39.956
two hours up and down to Amsterdam
经历两个小时的颠簸到阿姆斯特丹，

86
00:04:39.980 --> 00:04:41.900
just to get her treatment and tests."
就为了进行治疗和检查。”

87
00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:45.396
And that really breaks my heart,
这让我感到很伤心，

88
00:04:45.420 --> 00:04:48.916
because we all know that a professional nurse
因为我们都知道，一个专业的护士

89
00:04:48.940 --> 00:04:51.516
could draw her blood at home as well, right?
在家就可以进行抽血操作，对吧？

90
00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:55.156
And if she could get her tests and treatment at home as well,
如果她也能在家接受治疗和检查，

91
00:04:55.180 --> 00:04:58.556
she could do the things that are really important to her
就可以利用她生命的 最后几个月做一些

92
00:04:58.580 --> 00:05:00.180
in her last months.
真正对她重要的事情。

93
00:05:00.980 --> 00:05:04.740
My own mom, 82 years old now -- God bless her --
我的母亲，现在82岁了 ——老天保佑她——

94
00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:08.396
she's avoiding to go to the hospital
她不想去医院，

95
00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:12.356
because she finds it difficult to plan and manage the journey.
因为她发现很难规划和管理她的行程。

96
00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:15.356
So my sisters and I, we help her out.
于是我和妹妹会帮她搞定。

97
00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:18.596
But there's many elderly people who are avoiding care
但有很多不去医院的老年人，

98
00:05:18.620 --> 00:05:22.036
and are waiting that long that it becomes life-threatening,
拖的时间过长，到了危及生命的程度，

99
00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:24.740
and it's straight to the costly, intensive care.
不得不直接进入昂贵的重症监护环节。

100
00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:29.916
Dr. Covinsky, a clinical researcher at the University of California,
科文斯基博士，加州大学的临床研究员

101
00:05:29.940 --> 00:05:33.476
he concludes that a third of patients over 70
得出结论，1/3年龄超过70岁的人

102
00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:36.596
and more than half of patients over 85,
和超过一半年龄超过85岁的人，

103
00:05:36.620 --> 00:05:39.660
leave the hospital more disabled than when they came in.
离开医院时比他们进来的时候更糟糕。

104
00:05:41.180 --> 00:05:44.716
And a very practical problem
很多病人去医院

105
00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:48.196
that many patients face when they have to go to a hospital is:
不得不面临的一个实际问题是：

106
00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:52.756
Where do I go with my main companion in life,
我和我的主要生活伴侣要去哪里，

107
00:05:52.780 --> 00:05:54.420
where do I go with my dog?
我和我的狗要去哪里？

108
00:05:57.060 --> 00:05:59.116
That's our dog, by the way. Isn't she cute?
这是我的狗，她是不是很可爱？

109
00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:01.780
(Laughter)
（笑声）

110
00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:04.676
But it's not only about convenience.
但这并不只跟便利有关。

111
00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:08.820
It's also about unnecessary health care stays and costs.
它还涉及到不必要的医疗住宿和费用。

112
00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:11.076
A friend of mine, Art,
我的一个朋友，阿特，

113
00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:14.916
he recently needed to be hospitalized for just a minor surgery,
他最近需要住院接受一个小手术，

114
00:06:14.940 --> 00:06:17.676
and he had to stay in the hospital for over two weeks,
他不得不在医院呆两个星期，

115
00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:21.636
just because he needed a specific kind of IV antibiotics.
只是因为他需要 一种特殊的静脉抗生素。

116
00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:24.836
So he occupied a bed for two weeks
于是他占用了一张病床两周，

117
00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:27.636
that cost over a thousand euros a day.
每天需要花费超过1千欧。

118
00:06:27.660 --> 00:06:29.636
It's just ridiculous.
这真是荒谬。

119
00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:32.676
And these costs are really at the heart of the issue.
这些费用正是问题的核心。

120
00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:34.956
So we've seen over many of our global economies,
我们看到了很多全球经济中，

121
00:06:34.980 --> 00:06:38.156
health care expense grow as a percentage of GDP
医疗支出在GDP中的 占比在过去这些年

122
00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:39.876
over the last years.
一直在增长。

123
00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:42.836
So here we see that over the last 50 years,
在过去50年间，

124
00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:46.876
health care expense has grown from about five percent in Germany
医疗费用占比在德国从5%

125
00:06:46.900 --> 00:06:48.740
to about 11 percent now.
上升到现在的11%。

126
00:06:49.820 --> 00:06:54.780
In the US, we've seen growth from six percent to over 17 percent now.
在美国，这个比例从6%上升到17%。

127
00:06:55.980 --> 00:06:59.956
And a large portion of these costs are driven by investments
这些花费中很大部分来于

128
00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:02.740
in large, shiny hospital buildings.
对宏伟，熠熠生辉的医院建筑的投资。

129
00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:05.356
And these buildings are not flexible,
这些大楼并不灵活，

130
00:07:05.380 --> 00:07:08.516
and they maintain a system where hospital beds need to be filled
还维持着一个需要 让医院的床位被占满，

131
00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:10.180
for a hospital to run efficiently.
以保持医院效率的体系。

132
00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:14.500
There's no incentive for a hospital to run with less beds.
于是医院就没有动力减少床位。

133
00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:17.900
Just the thought of that makes you sick, right?
一想到这个你就恶心，是吧？

134
00:07:18.780 --> 00:07:22.516
And here's the thing: the cost for treating my buddy Art at home
事实上：我的朋友阿特在家治疗的费用

135
00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:25.780
can be up to 10 times cheaper than hospital care.
要比医在院的花费便宜10倍。

136
00:07:27.060 --> 00:07:28.540
And that is where we're headed.
那就是我们前进的方向。

137
00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:32.660
The hospital bed of the future will be in our own homes.
医院未来的床位在我们自己的家中。

138
00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:35.396
And it's already starting.
而且这种趋势已经开始了。

139
00:07:35.420 --> 00:07:39.436
Global home care is growing 10 percent year over year.
全球家庭护理正在以 每年10%的速度增长。

140
00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:44.036
And from my own experience, I see that logistics and technology
从我个人的经验来看，物流和技术

141
00:07:44.060 --> 00:07:46.540
are making these home health care solutions work.
让家庭医疗护理变得可行。

142
00:07:48.060 --> 00:07:50.356
Technology is already allowing us to do things
技术让我们可以做过去

143
00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:52.420
that were once exclusive to hospitals.
只有医院才能做的事情。

144
00:07:53.540 --> 00:07:55.220
Diagnosis tests like blood,
如血液，

145
00:07:56.220 --> 00:08:00.876
glucose tests, urine tests, can now be taken in the comfort of our homes.
葡萄糖和尿液检测那样的诊断测试， 现在可以在舒适的家中进行。

146
00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:03.620
And more and more connected devices
越来越多的联网设备，

147
00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:07.916
we see like pacemakers and insulin pumps
如心脏起搏器和胰岛素泵，

148
00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:11.580
that will proactively signal if help is needed soon.
在紧急情况下会发出预警信号。

149
00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:14.716
And all that technology is coming together
所有这些技术组合在一起

150
00:08:14.740 --> 00:08:18.036
in much more insights into the patients' health,
可以更加深入地理解病人的健康，

151
00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:22.076
and that insight and all of the information leads to better control
这样的剖析和所有这些信息 可以带来更好的控制，

152
00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:24.156
and to less medical errors --
并减少医疗事故——

153
00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:26.956
remember, the third cause of death
记住，这可是美国第三大

154
00:08:26.980 --> 00:08:28.180
in the US.
死因。

155
00:08:29.420 --> 00:08:31.156
And I see it every day at work.
我每天都在工作中见证这些。

156
00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:32.876
I work in logistics
我工作在物流领域，

157
00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:36.380
and for me, home health care works.
对我而言，家庭医护的确可行。

158
00:08:37.860 --> 00:08:41.996
So we see a delivery driver deliver the medicine
我们看到送货司机运输药物

159
00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:43.220
to the patient's home.
到患者家中。

160
00:08:44.300 --> 00:08:47.756
A nurse joins him and actually administers the drug
护士与他一道，在患者家中

161
00:08:47.780 --> 00:08:48.979
at the patient's home.
进行管理药物。

162
00:08:50.499 --> 00:08:52.196
It's that simple.
就是这么简单。

163
00:08:52.220 --> 00:08:53.835
Remember my buddy, Art?
还记得我的朋友，阿特？

164
00:08:53.859 --> 00:08:57.636
He can now get the IV antibiotics in the comfort of his home:
他现在可以在舒适的家中 获得静脉注射抗生素：

165
00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:01.396
no hospital pajamas, no crappy food
不需要穿病号服，吃难吃的病号餐，

166
00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:06.276
and no risk of these antibiotic-resistant superbugs
也不会面临被只存在于 医院中的那些耐抗生素的

167
00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:08.676
that only bite you in these hospitals.
超级病菌叮咬的风险。

168
00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:09.956
And it goes further.
好处还不止于此。

169
00:09:09.980 --> 00:09:14.476
So now the elderly people can get the treatment that they need
现在老年人也可以在他们舒适的家中

170
00:09:14.500 --> 00:09:16.476
in the comfort of their own home
获得所需要的治疗，

171
00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:18.996
while with their best companion in life.
同时有生活中最佳伴侣陪同。

172
00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:22.356
And there's no need anymore to drive hours and hours
也不再需要开车几个小时，

173
00:09:22.380 --> 00:09:24.260
just to get your treatment and tests.
只是为了获得医疗和检查。

174
00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:27.036
In the Netherlands and in Denmark,
在荷兰和丹麦，

175
00:09:27.060 --> 00:09:29.756
we've seen very good successes in cancer clinics
我们在癌症诊所看到了

176
00:09:29.780 --> 00:09:32.940
organizing chemotherapies at the patient's homes,
在病人家中组织化疗的非常成功的例子，

177
00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:36.500
sometimes even together with fellow patients.
有时候甚至几个病友一起。

178
00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:40.436
The best improvements for these patients
对于这些病人而言，

179
00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:43.956
have been improvements in reduction in stress,
最大的改善在于压力、

180
00:09:43.980 --> 00:09:46.540
anxiety disorders and depression.
焦虑障碍和抑郁的减轻。

181
00:09:47.740 --> 00:09:51.396
Home health care also helped them to get back a sense of normality
家庭医护也帮助他们找回了生活中的

182
00:09:51.420 --> 00:09:53.756
and freedom in their lives,
正常和自由的感觉，

183
00:09:53.780 --> 00:09:57.820
and they've actually helped them to forget about their disease.
这其实也帮助他们忘记了病痛。

184
00:09:59.420 --> 00:10:02.036
But home health care, Niels --
但关于家庭医护，尼尔斯——

185
00:10:02.060 --> 00:10:05.956
what if I don't even have a home, when I'm homeless,
如果我没有家，当我无家可归时，

186
00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:09.356
or when I do have a home but there's no one to take care of me
或者当我有家，但没人可以照看我，

187
00:10:09.380 --> 00:10:11.060
or even open up the door?
或者连开窗户都没人帮忙时怎么办？

188
00:10:11.860 --> 00:10:15.236
Well, in comes our sharing economy,
这个时候我们的共享经济就发挥作用了。

189
00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:19.156
or, as I like to call it, the Airbnb for home care.
或者，我喜欢称之为，家庭医护爱彼迎。

190
00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:22.516
In the Netherlands, we see churches and care organizations
在荷兰，我们看到教堂和护理机构

191
00:10:22.540 --> 00:10:25.396
match people in need of care and company
会将需要护理和陪伴的人们，

192
00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:27.556
with people who actually have a home for them
与有家并能提供医护

193
00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:29.540
and can provide care and company to them.
和陪伴的人们进行匹配。

194
00:10:30.340 --> 00:10:32.236
Home health care is cheaper,
家庭医护更便宜，

195
00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:35.876
it's easier to facilitate, and it's quick to set up --
它易于安置，可以快速投入使用——

196
00:10:35.900 --> 00:10:40.476
in these rural areas we talked about, but also in humanitarian crisis situations
在这些我们谈到的农村地区， 也在人道主义危机的情况下，

197
00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:46.180
where it's often safer, quicker and cheaper to set things up at home.
把医疗设施放在家里通常 要更加安全，快速和廉价。

198
00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:52.116
Home health care is very applicable in prosperous areas
家庭医护非常适用于繁荣地区，

199
00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:55.716
but also very much in underserved communities.
但在服务水平低下的社区也是如此。

200
00:10:55.740 --> 00:10:57.876
Home health care works in developed countries
家庭护理对发达国家有效，

201
00:10:57.900 --> 00:10:59.620
as well as in developing countries.
对发展中国家也是如此。

202
00:11:00.580 --> 00:11:06.396
So I'm passionate to help facilitate improvements in patients' lives
因此，我非常热衷于通过家庭医护服务

203
00:11:06.420 --> 00:11:08.356
due to home health care.
帮助改善病人的生活。

204
00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:10.796
I'm passionate to help facilitate
我热衷于帮助

205
00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:13.556
that the elderly people get the treatment that they need
那些老年人在自己舒适的家中

206
00:11:13.580 --> 00:11:15.316
in the comfort of their own homes,
获得所需要的治疗，

207
00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:17.380
together with their best companion in life.
有他们生活中最佳伴侣的陪伴。

208
00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:20.956
I'm passionate to make the change
我热衷于推动改变，

209
00:11:20.980 --> 00:11:24.556
and help ensure that patients, and not their disease,
帮助确保是病人，而不是他们的疾病

210
00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:26.140
are in control of their lives.
在掌控他们的生活。

211
00:11:26.900 --> 00:11:29.796
To me, that is health care delivered at home.
对我而言，这就是医疗护理上门服务。

212
00:11:29.820 --> 00:11:31.036
Thank you.
谢谢。

213
00:11:31.060 --> 00:11:34.820
(Applause)
（鼓掌）